rc":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q05","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"**Without using a calculator**, work out $\\dfrac{1}{15} + \\dfrac{2}{5}$.\n\nWrite down all the steps of your working and give your answer as a fraction in its simplest form.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q06","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":6,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q06","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Solve.\n\\[\n    7m - 2 \\geqslant 19\n\\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"solve"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q07","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":7,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.2","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Sets","qtype":"sets and Venn diagrams","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q07","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"$C = \\{x : x \\text{ is an integer and } 5 < x < 12\\}$ \\qquad $D = \\{5, 10\\}$\n\n(a) Put a ring around the correct statement from the list below.\n\n    $D = \\varnothing$ \\qquad $C \\cap D = \\{10\\}$ \\qquad $6 \\in D$ \\qquad $D \\subset C$\n\n\n(b) Find $\\text{n}(C \\cup D)$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q08","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":8,"marks":2,"topics":["Number","Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.2","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Algebraic manipulation","qtype":"algebraic manipulation","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q08","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Factorise.\n\\[\n    xy + 5y + 2x + 10\n\\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"simplify"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q09","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":9,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.9","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Estimation","qtype":"estimation and rounding","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q09","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"There are $30\\,000$ lions in Africa.\n\nThe number of lions in Africa decreases exponentially by $2\\%$ each year.\n\nFind the number of lions in Africa after 6 years.\n\nGive your answer correct to the nearest hundred.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q10","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":10,"marks":2,"topics":["Coordinate geometry"],"s":"3.1","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q10","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Find the mid-point of $AB$ where $A = (w, r)$ and $B = (3w, t)$.\n\nGive your answer in its simplest form in terms of $w$, $r$ and $t$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"(.......... , ..........)"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q11","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":11,"marks":2,"topics":["Number","Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"1.10","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Limits of accuracy","qtype":"limits of accuracy","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q11","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"An equilateral triangle has side length $12\\,\\text{cm}$, correct to the nearest centimetre.\n\nFind the lower bound and the upper bound of the perimeter of the triangle.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"multiline","lines":2,"layout":"column","template":"Lower bound $=$ ____ cm\\nUpper bound $=$ ____ cm"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q12","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":12,"marks":2,"topics":["Geometry","Trigonometry"],"s":"4.6","d":2,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Angles","qtype":"angle calculations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q12","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"$x^\\circ$ is an **obtuse** angle and $\\sin x^\\circ = 0.43$.\n\nFind the value of $x$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"number","prefix":"x ="}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q13","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":13,"marks":2,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.7","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Sequences","qtype":"sequences","g":"sequence","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q13","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"These are the first five terms of a sequence.\n\\[\n    -4 \\quad 2 \\quad 8 \\quad 14 \\quad 20\n\\]\n\nFind an expression for the $n$th term of this sequence.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q14","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":14,"marks":3,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.6","d":2,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Inequalities","qtype":"inequalities","g":"inequality","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q14","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"By shading the **unwanted** regions of the grid, find and label the region $R$ that satisfies the following four inequalities.\n\\[\n    x \\leqslant 3 \\qquad x \\geqslant 2 \\qquad y \\leqslant 2x + 1 \\qquad y \\geqslant 4 - x\n\\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q15","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":15,"marks":3,"topics":["Transformations and vectors"],"s":"7.1","d":2,"cat":"vectors","topic":"Transformations","qtype":"transformations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q15","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"\\[\n    \\mathbf{M} = \\begin{pmatrix} 5 & -3 \\\\ -1 & 2 \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\n\n(a) Find $3\\mathbf{M}$.\n\n    \n\n(b) Find $\\mathbf{M}^{-1}$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1,"answer":{"type":"number","prefix":"3\\mathbf{M} ="}},{"label":"(b)","marks":2,"answer":{"type":"number","prefix":"\\mathbf{M}⁻¹ ="}}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q16","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":16,"marks":3,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q16","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"\\[\n    x^2 - 12x + a = (x + b)^2\n\\]\n\nFind the value of $a$ and the value of $b$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"multiline","lines":2,"layout":"column","template":"a = ____\\nb = ____"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q17","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":17,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"3.7","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Perpendicular lines","qtype":"perpendicular lines","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q17","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows the points $C(-1, 2)$ and $D(9, 7)$.\n\nFind the equation of the line perpendicular to $CD$ that passes through the point $(1, 3)$.\n\nGive your answer in the form $y = mx + c$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"number","prefix":"y ="}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q18","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":18,"marks":4,"topics":["Geometry","Mensuration","Statistics"],"s":"4.7","d":2,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Circle theorems","qtype":"circle theorems","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q18","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"120 students choose what they want to do when they leave school.\n\nTheir choices are shown in the table.\n\n\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\nChoice & Number of students \\\\\n\\hline\nUniversity & 57 \\\\\n\\hline\nTraining & 45 \\\\\n\\hline\nWork & 18 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{tabular}\nComplete the pie chart to show this information.\n\nLabel each sector clearly.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"complete","texHtml":"120 students choose what they want to do when they leave school.\n\nTheir choices are shown in the table.\n\n<div class=\"pp-table-wrap\"><table class=\"pp-table\"><tr><th style=\"text-align:center\">Choice</th><th style=\"text-align:center\">Number of students</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">University</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">57</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Training</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">45</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">Work</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td></tr></table></div>\nComplete the pie chart to show this information.\n\nLabel each sector clearly."},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q19","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":19,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"3.1","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q19","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows a pentagon $ABCDE$.\n\n(a) **Using a straight edge and compasses only**, construct the bisector of angle $BCD$.\n\n\n(b) Draw the locus of the points inside the pentagon that are $3\\,\\text{cm}$ from $E$.\n\n\n(c) Shade the region inside the pentagon that is\n    \\begin{itemize}\n\n(d) less than $3\\,\\text{cm}$ from $E$\n    \\end{itemize}\n    and\n    \\begin{itemize}\n\n(e) nearer to $DC$ than to $BC$.\n    \\end{itemize}","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":1},{"label":"(c)","marks":0},{"label":"(d)","marks":0},{"label":"(e)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q20","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":20,"marks":4,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q20","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Make $m$ the subject of the formula.\n\\[\n    x = \\frac{3m}{2 - m}\n\\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"rearrange","answer":{"type":"number","prefix":"m ="}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q21","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":21,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"3.4","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Length and midpoint","qtype":"length and midpoint","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q21","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows an equilateral triangle $ABC$ with sides of length $10\\,\\text{cm}$.\n\n$AMN$ is a sector of a circle, centre $A$.\n\n$M$ is the mid-point of $AC$.\n\nWork out the area of the shaded region.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate","answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"cm²"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q22","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":22,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"3.1","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q22","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows a cuboid with dimensions $5.5\\,\\text{cm}$, $8\\,\\text{cm}$ and $16.2\\,\\text{cm}$.\n\nCalculate the angle between the line $AB$ and the horizontal base of the cuboid.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q23","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":23,"marks":4,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.1","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"Types of number","qtype":"types of number","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q23","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"(a) Write 56 as a product of its prime factors.\n\n    \n\n(b) Find the lowest common multiple (LCM) of 56 and 42.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q24","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":24,"marks":5,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Transformations and vectors","Statistics"],"s":"3.1","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q24","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The time, $t$ minutes, 80 students each spend completing their homework is recorded.\n\nThe cumulative frequency diagram shows the results.\n\nUse the cumulative frequency diagram to find an estimate of\n\n(a) the median,\n\n    \n\n(b) the interquartile range,\n\n    \n\n(c) the number of students who spend more than 40 minutes completing their homework.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"min"}},{"label":"(b)","marks":2,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"min"}},{"label":"(c)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper22-Q25","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper22","qnum":25,"marks":5,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":2,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/22/O/N/18 Q25","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"(a) $\\text{f}(x) = x^3$ \\qquad $\\text{g}(x) = 5x + 2$\n\n    (i)  Find $\\text{gf}(x)$.\n\n        \n\n         Find $\\text{g}^{-1}(x)$.\n\n        \n\n(b) $\\text{h}(x) = ax^2 + 1$\n\n    Find the value of $a$ when $\\text{h}(-2) = 21$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":2,"answer":{"type":"number","prefix":"a ="}}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"}]